---
import Article from '../layouts/Article.astro';

const title = 'Cock Hero funscripts: script beat-driven edits with AI - FunGen';
const description =
  'Cock Hero edits follow the music, not the on-screen action. FunGen scripts them from the audio track - beat detection, snap-to-beat and BPM stroke generation - on your own machine.';
const canonicalPath = '/cock-hero-funscripts';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');

const articleLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'Cock Hero funscripts: script beat-driven edits with AI',
  description,
  inLanguage: 'en',
  dateModified: '2026-07-21',
  mainEntityOfPage: 'https://fungen.app/cock-hero-funscripts',
  author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'FunGen' },
  publisher: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'FunGen',
    logo: { '@type': 'ImageObject', url: 'https://fungen.app/icon-512.png' },
  },
};
const breadcrumbs = [{ name: 'Cock Hero funscripts', path: '/cock-hero-funscripts' }];
---

<Article
  {title}
  {description}
  heading="Funscripts for Cock Hero"
  {canonicalPath}
  {articleLd}
  {breadcrumbs}
>
  <p class="lead">
    <strong>Cock Hero</strong> edits are paced by the <strong>music</strong>. The stroke follows the
    beat, the tempo changes on purpose, and the on-screen footage is cut to match - which makes them
    a different scripting problem from a normal scene. <a href={`${base}/`}>FunGen</a> scripts them
    from the <strong>audio track</strong> rather than the picture.
  </p>

  <h2>Why motion tracking is the wrong tool here</h2>
  <p>
    An <a href={`${base}/generate-funscripts-from-video/`}>AI motion tracker</a> works by following
    movement between frames. That is exactly right for a continuous POV scene, and exactly wrong for
    a Cock Hero edit: the source cuts every few seconds, jumps between performers and angles, and
    frequently shows footage whose motion has nothing to do with the beat you are meant to stroke
    to. Tracking that footage faithfully would produce a script that fights the music.
  </p>
  <p>
    The signal that actually carries a Cock Hero round is the <strong>audio</strong>. So that is what
    FunGen reads.
  </p>

  <h2>Beat-driven generation</h2>
  <p>
    FunGen analyses the video's audio for <strong>onsets</strong> - the percussive hits that define
    the beat - and lays keyframes on them. You control how it turns those beats into strokes:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Alternate top/bottom</strong> - one beat up, the next down, the classic pattern.</li>
    <li><strong>Fixed</strong> - a hit on every beat from a held position.</li>
    <li><strong>Top and bottom positions</strong> - set the stroke range the round should use.</li>
    <li>
      <strong>Sensitivity</strong> - tighten it for a sparse kick pattern, loosen it to pick up
      faster percussion.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Because it reads the real audio, a round that <strong>changes tempo</strong> mid-way is followed
    rather than averaged over.
  </p>

  <h2>Then tighten it by hand</h2>
  <p>
    Beat detection gets the timing skeleton right; the taste is yours. FunGen's
    <a href={`${base}/funscript-editor/`}>frame-accurate editor</a> gives you
    <strong>snap-to-beat</strong> so every manual edit lands on the grid, beat markers on the
    minimap for orientation, and <strong>BPM stroke generation</strong> to fill a range with an
    exact rate or an exact number of strokes. Chapters let you treat each round separately, so a
    slow build and a fast finish can carry different stroke ranges.
  </p>

  <h2>Instruction rounds and held sections</h2>
  <p>
    Most Cock Hero edits include sections that are not simple stroking - holds, edges, pauses on an
    instruction card. Those are best placed deliberately rather than generated: mark the span, set
    the position, and let the beat generation resume after it. The
    <a href={`${base}/studio/`}>Doctor</a> then checks the finished script for gaps, device speed
    limits and timing problems before you play it.
  </p>

  <h2>Script your own rounds</h2>
  <p>
    Load the edit, let FunGen read the audio, choose a pattern, and refine on the timeline.
    Everything runs locally on your own machine, so nothing is uploaded. The result plays to
    <a href={`${base}/supported-devices/`}>any supported device</a> -
    <strong>The Handy</strong>, <strong>OSR2 / SR6</strong>, or anything on
    <strong>Buttplug.io / Intiface</strong>. <a href={`${base}/#pricing`}>Download FunGen</a> and
    try it on a round you already have.
  </p>
</Article>
